# Linux File System Navigation Fundamentals

## Learning Objectives

After completing this tutorial, you will be able to:

* Understand Linux file system hierarchy
* Navigate directories using `cd`
* Understand absolute and relative paths
* Return to previous directories
* Access command documentation using `man`

---

## Linux File System Hierarchy

Linux stores files in a hierarchical structure that starts from the root directory `/`.

```text
/
├── bin
├── boot
├── dev
├── etc
├── home
│   ├── nilesh
│   └── minesh
├── opt
├── proc
├── root
├── tmp
├── usr
└── var
```

### Common Directories

| Directory | Purpose                    |
| --------- | -------------------------- |
| /         | Root directory             |
| /home     | User home directories      |
| /root     | Root user's home directory |
| /etc      | Configuration files        |
| /var      | Log and variable data      |
| /tmp      | Temporary files            |
| /usr      | User applications          |
| /opt      | Optional software packages |

---

## Display Current Directory

Use the `pwd` command.

```bash
pwd
```

Example:

```bash
$ pwd
/home/nilesh
```

---

## Absolute Path

An absolute path always starts from the root directory `/`.

Examples:

```bash
/home/nilesh
/tmp
/etc
/usr/local
```

Navigate using an absolute path:

```bash
cd /tmp
```

You can execute this command from any location.

---

## Relative Path

A relative path starts from your current location.

Assume current directory:

```bash
/home/nilesh
```

Move to Downloads:

```bash
cd Downloads
```

Move to Documents:

```bash
cd ../Documents
```

Relative paths do not start with `/`.

---

## Using the cd Command

### Move to another directory

```bash
cd /tmp
```

---

### Move to home directory

```bash
cd
```

or

```bash
cd ~
```

---

### Move one level up

```bash
cd ..
```

Example:

```text
/home/nilesh/Documents
        ↑
        cd ..
```

Result:

```text
/home/nilesh
```

---

### Return to previous directory

```bash
cd -
```

Example:

```bash
$ pwd
/home/nilesh

$ cd /tmp

$ cd -

/home/nilesh
```

---

## Current Directory Symbol

The dot (`.`) represents the current directory.

```bash
cd .
```

No directory change occurs.

---

## Parent Directory Symbol

Two dots (`..`) represent the parent directory.

```bash
cd ..
```

Example:

```text
/tmp/project/dev
           ↑
           cd ..
```

Result:

```text
/tmp/project
```

---

## Accessing Help

Linux provides built-in documentation.

Open manual page:

```bash
man cd
```

Open ls documentation:

```bash
man ls
```

---

## Navigating Inside man Pages

Search text:

```text
/error
```

Next match:

```text
n
```

Previous match:

```text
N
```

Quit:

```text
q
```

